article.headline: TCU's best game not good enough vs. Lady Vols
article.linkText: TCU's best game not good enough to beat Lady Vols
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- If only TCU played like this every night. Maybe playing No. 3 Tennessee close was the boost the Lady Frogs needed.

Kara Lawson had 20 points, seven assists and seven rebounds and
Gwen Jackson added 14 points as the Lady Vols held off TCU 86-72 Tuesday night.

The Lady Frogs (10-12) never led, but had a late 7-0 run to cut the lead to 74-70 with 6:05 remaining.

The Lady Vols (21-3) responded with a 10-2 run over the next four minutes to earn their 12th consecutive win since losing last month to Connecticut.

Tennessee coach Pat Summitt had nothing but good things to say about TCU and probably wondered how the Lady Frogs had lost 12 games.

``She was very complimentary of our team's heart and effort
tonight. I told the team she let me know that 'your team is one of
those teams that can be a Top 25 team if they play like that every
night,' `` TCU coach Jeff Mittie said. ``This team does have
potential. We haven't played to that potential most of the year.''

Tennessee, playing in its third home game in six days, beat Mississippi by 43 points last Thursday and Florida by 39 on Sunday. TCU was a different story.

The Lady Frogs have been hot and cold this season, beating then-No. 9 Vanderbilt by 17 points in a four-game winning streak and then losing four straight last month. They were not intimidated by Tennessee and played as if this was an NCAA Tournament game.

The Lady Frogs pulled within a point at the break by finishing the first half with an 8-2 run.

Tennessee started the second half with a 6-1 run on a basket by Jackson and two by Lawson.

The Lady Vols stretched their lead to 11 point on Jackson's inside basket with 7:43 left, but TCU trimmed the lead again with a 7-0 run. That was as close as the Lady Frogs got the rest of the way.

``I thought that TCU played great. If I was their coach, I'd be pleased with how they played tonight and not real happy that they played this way just tonight,'' Summitt said. ``If they were in our league, they would be in the top eight, personnel-wise.''

Tasha Butts added 11 points and 11 rebounds, and Courtney McDaniel had 11 points for Tennessee.

The Lady Frogs, who made nine 3-pointers, were led by Ebony
Shaw's 16 points. Tiffany Evans added 15 points and Amy Pack 14.

TCU found a way to challenge Tennessee despite a roller-coaster year.

``I don't remember them hitting that many 3s on tape,'' Lawson said. ``I think that we're used to teams looking better against us than they do on tape. We know we're going to get every team's best game.''

Shaw and Evans came off the bench as Mittie substituted like it
was a hockey game. He replaced four and sometimes all five about
every five minutes.

Evans hit a 3, and Shaw made another with 0.4 seconds left to cut the lead to 41-40 at halftime.

The Lady Vols started the game with an 11-0 run, but TCU battled back quickly and cut it to two four times and finally down to one point when Pack hit a 3 with 6:30 remaining before halftime.
